</td></tr>
						
		<tr>
			
			<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>

						
							
				
								
				<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=36153' class="auth_text" style="font-weight:bold;"><span style='color:#336600;'>Meresya</span></a>
				<br>

								
				<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
									Journeyman
								<br>
									Posts: 41<br>
													Registered: 05-20-2004
				
				</span>
									<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
								
				<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=36153'>			
	
		</a><br>

				<span class=text_smallest>
								</span>

								
			
			
									<p>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
										Viewed 287 times<br>
									</span>

									<img src='/i/skins/default/icon_rating_5.gif' border=0 alt='4 ratings - 5.0 average' width=55 height=10>
									</td>

						<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#0C142B" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												<DIV>The deviations between the different definitions tend to show how the bard class has changed in focus from the original release.&nbsp; The newest incarnation of the definition from EQLive is pretty much well on the mark, hower it is missing half of the definition, that is it has it covered by a lump sum of bards being able to do a little bit of everything.&nbsp; Again, which isn't totally accurate, but is close.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The problem with definitions in EQ is that there are two&nbsp;types on a definition, as well as two classifications.&nbsp; A class has a melee and magic type definition.&nbsp; Some classes don't include magic, but all classes include melee (even if only at a subpar, not worth the time to do amount).&nbsp; Some classes don't have magic, while others do.&nbsp; Whether it is melee or magic, both types have a classification of either being offensive or defensive.&nbsp; Some overlapping occurs, but in general there is a distict classification of one or other per class.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I'll let someone else with more time post each class with their respective category types and classifications, as I don't have the time at present.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Tanks are defensive by nature, meaning their classification is defensive, while they may posses offensive capabilities, the majority of their capabilities is in defense.&nbsp; Some have magical abilities, again there is a classification for the magic aspects as well, and appear to follow the same general format.&nbsp; Generally speaking a defensive melee class could possess a classification of defensive or offensive with regards to the magical while still being considered defensive in nature.&nbsp; This is a balancing so to speak, allowing for variations between classes, as well deviations.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The same holds true for pure magic classes, being classified as either offensive or defensive.&nbsp; Again, just because there is a classification of offensive or defensive doesn't mean that there isn't any opposite type spells, allowing for some form of balance inherent in the class, as well as with other classes.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The problem at higher end content with bards is exactly this definitional placement at present.&nbsp; Bards are technically classified as defensive with respect to melee, hence doing the lowest damage of all the melee classes, as well as having the lowest mitigation of all the melee classes.&nbsp; Yet we have no form of effectively gaining agro to fulfill a role as a defensive class, effectively removing bards from the role.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Bards are most likely classified as defensive with respects to magic, from the standpoint that while a lot of our songs are offensive in nature for our groups, they can be preceived to be a defensive measure for the group.&nbsp; Of course, this is totally subject to point of view, so can fall on either side of the spectrum.&nbsp; An additional way to look at it is that we are neither, as we can do both.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Once again we look back at the definition which states bards can do a little bit of everything, and find that herein lies the problem.&nbsp; We do a little of everything, but everything is at the lowest available amount compared to parent classes.&nbsp; Bards don't posses anything unique to them to classify us on one side or other of the defensive - offensive spectrum, effectively putting us in a classification of both.&nbsp; The amount of immune mobs and highly resistent mobs have taken away a lot of our defensive abilities that we do posses, even in their limited capacities.&nbsp; The amount of mob hitpoints, along with other apsects have greatly reduces what offensive capabilities we bring.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>We have the worse mana efficient nukes in game, compounded&nbsp;by the worst mana regeneration in the game.&nbsp; We also have the most limiting&nbsp;mana regeneration options available in the game.&nbsp; We have the lowest dot damage in the game (against higher end content, such that the number of dots we can effectively land is basically cut in half, and of those they tend to only land like half the time, give or take).</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>We have a grand total of four activateable disciplines, of which three are on defensive.&nbsp; One is on a timer of an hour - deftdance, making it valued as a last ditch attempt in certain situations.&nbsp; The other two are resists in nature, also on up to a 30 minute timer.&nbsp; The offensive one - puretone -has already been complained about as being subpar at present, both on the modifier given as well as the reuse timer.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>We have a total of two activated aas - Fading Memories and Boastful Bellow, with one - Exultant Bellow - having a high cost upgrade returning less return vs cost at each level of upgrade increase.&nbsp; Bellow is used purely as a pulling tool, while seeing use as inconsequential added damage.&nbsp; Occasionally it is used to effect casters, but again suffers from reuse timer overload compared to caster npc's recast times.&nbsp; Fading Memories is clearly a defense aa, but also utilized in tricky pulling situations or to drop us off of a mob's rampage list.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Every other magic class has a method of bringing offensive spells to bear on mobs in burst type damage except bards.&nbsp; Compound the problem with mana regeneration are bards are basically totally removed from any form of burst damage.&nbsp; Our offensive songs are mostly group, again, no inherent burst damage capabilities.&nbsp; Basically putting bards directly in the middle of the defensive offensive classification for magic, with no clear cut offsetting aspect.&nbsp; In a way this puts bards in a classification of both with respect to melee and magic, which also tends to support why all the current topics of proposed fixes, in an attempt to regain some kind of clear cut position within the classifications.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Polara Magami</DIV>
																		
										</td></tr>
