			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
FeroceFV wrote:<BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV>Since the name of this forum is Bard Definition Discussion, I think it would be a good idea to discuss our class definition.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Here is the definition of bards on EQLive, in the Library section:</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff00><SPAN class=""><BR>Bards can do a little bit of everything. Their songs can regenerate health and mana, increase attack speed and accuracy, momentarily charm angry enemies, help friends resist many types of damage and even directly damage enemies. Bards are perhaps best known, however, for their ability to greatly increase the foot speed of their group.<BR><BR>Bards have the unique ability to create multiple effects at once. By weaving different songs together, a bard can customize effects to any situation. This makes nimble fingers and quick thinking a must for those who want to play a bard.<BR><BR>Bards do well both alone and in groups. With the right combination of songs, they can adapt to many different challenges. The bard is a great class for players who enjoy a wide variety of play options but are quick to adapt to a changing situation.</SPAN> </FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>What do you all think of these definitions?</DIV>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Changing "little bit of everything" to "huge range of abilities" was a good call - The EQLive statement is a little misleading.&nbsp; I also agree with leaving out the "greatly increase foot speed of the group" as the defining ability of the bard.&nbsp; Definitely leave out the "unique ability to create multiple effects at once" part - this is really misleading - as other spellcasters can have all sorts of spell effects in play at a time.</P>
<P>Regarding the Allakhazam definition - that one has a lot of outdated or misleading statements as well, and I'm glad to see you're not repeating them in your definition.&nbsp; If you're going to include notes about grouping, it should be noted that if you are a social player who likes to chat, you likely will need to make a choice between your effectiveness in groups and being able to chat with those you are grouped with.&nbsp; Also, if including&nbsp;any notes about how playing a bard will work,&nbsp;they&nbsp;should give a brief overview of how twisting is done - compared to the spellcasting system used by other classes in EQ.&nbsp; Finally, if you really wanted to I suppose you could rate bards by the numbers on their mitigation, combat skill caps, aggro-gaining ability, and disciplines, as well as what options the AA choices can give for those wanting to bring their bard into a more focused role later in their career.&nbsp; I would think that pulling and crowd control (and solo potential) would be the things that&nbsp;a bard could contend with first place for, when comparing what classes do what best.&nbsp; I think the bard can fill&nbsp;the primary group role in those situations (cc &amp; puller).</P>
																		
										</td></tr>
